Input.summary_text: The four - poster oak wood bed was dumped in car park of Redland House Hotel in Chester and later sold at auction for £ 2,200 . TV historian Jonathan Foyle has spent years trying to prove the artefact's historical roots and has now revealed that DNA testing on the bed's timber proved it once belonged to King Henry VII . He has traced it back to 1495 , when Henry VII went to Lathom in Lancashire to see the Stanley family , who had helped him to victory in the Battle of Bosworth in 1485 . The bed also features carvings of biblical scenes of Henry and his wife Elizabeth of York styled as Adam and Eve .

Input.summary_text: The four - poster oak wood bed was dumped in car park of Redland House Hotel in Chester and later sold at auction for £ 2,200 . TV historian Jonathan Foyle has spent years trying to prove the artefact's historical roots and has now revealed that DNA testing on the bed's timber proved it once belonged to King Henry VII . He has traced it back to 1495 , when Henry VII went to Lathom in Lancashire to see the Stanley family , who had helped him to victory in the Battle of Bosworth in 1485 . The bed also features carvings of biblical scenes of Henry and his wife Elizabeth of York styled as Adam and Eve .
